pan><br>  Posts: 324<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(10/18/02 2:01:51 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1582.topic&index=28>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://mywebpages.comcast.net/drichardson38/images/cloud-uinin.gif WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_question_mark.gif" align=absmiddle>  Confessions of a Curmudgeon</span><hr size=1> OK - a few points I feel compelled to make here... take em or leave em. I'm no Dean Rusk or Richard Holbrooke, but here you are...<br>
<br>
1.  There is an important distinction between nationalism, patriotism, and jingoism.  Patriotism is a good thing... it implies that one will work to preserve what is good and fix what is bad about one's nation.  Nationalism is a mixed bag... for the oppressed and those that celebrate their culture, huzzah.  For those that use it as a matter of individualistic foreign policy, it shows a lack of global perspective.  Jingoism is what we have to defend against internally, as the previous two points can develop to the third if left unchecked.<br>
<br>
Don't be afraid to be proud of your nation and your culture.  But don't be afraid to be challenged and don't be afraid to point out what is wrong either.<br>
<br>
2.  The U.S. is not a democracy, it is a democratic republic.  It seems like a small difference, but without the ability for the general populace to vote on every matter of policy, the voting public's only way to influence policy is through a) voting and b) public outcry during non-voting terms.  <br>
<br>
Those who defend leaders and policy without question, carrying the jingoism banner (NOT patriotism) do their own nation a disservice.  A republic NEEDS the whingers and the dissidents.  It cannot rest on mooers.  The mooers are a bigger problem than the whingers, because the mooers accept the bad with the good.<br>
<br>
3.  I would hazard a guess that the biggest reason the U.S. will be more diplomatic with North Korea ... China.  While not &quot;allies&quot; per se, the Chinese very likely would come to the defense of North Korea if the U.S. were to try to attack.<br>
<br>
That would be a Bad Thing.<br>
<br>
Also, don't think that a conflict in North Korea - even one that didn't include China - would be a simple matter of air strikes.  The rugged terrain of the Korean penninsula and dense ground cover makes anything but carpet bombing or close in helicopter rocket attacks really effective.<br>
<br>
Plus, there's the added complication of airspace.  I doubt even a neutral China would allow U.S. warplanes to cross into their space, and South Korea, Japan, the former USSR states, and the Phillippines would all be very susceptible to reprisals afterwards - suggesting a long-term holding force being station in the region, on top what is already there now.<br>
<br>
4.  Terrorism is a tool of those that are unable to face an enemy head on, and is usually only considered after other avenues are exhausted.  It is usually a direct action against the general populace to provoke a reaction from the head.<br>
<br>
Anybody who immediately dismisses the (at least) partial responsibility of U.S. foreign policy in the creation of terrorist states isn't paying attention...<br>
<br>
5. ... or getting his news from FOX.  <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> <br>
Let me ask you, where in the Media do you hear that this is still the Greastest Country in the world? You don't. Ever. The media is run by liberal hacks. The only station out there that is remotely close to have dual opinions is Fox News. Which, btw.. has the Number 1 and 2 Rated Nightly News Cable shows.<br>
<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Actually, that's a bit pointed.   Rupert Murdoch's newspaper properties are outageously opinionated right-wing tripe, and have garnered a fair bit of popularity not necessarily for their content, but for the bullheaded bellicosity of the writing.  It's not news, it's entertainment.<br>
<br>
The &quot;Liberal&quot; media - comprised of massive mutlinational profit-driven conglomerates - aren't much better.  But don't fool yourself, media is a mirror of the public at large... they don't feed us a liberal agenda unless it sells more papers.  Why do you think the Food &amp; Wine section of your local paper is larger than the international news page?<br>
<br>
I would argue the value of having &quot;dual opinions.&quot;  I don't WANT my media to have opinions.  I want them to present facts.  I'll form my own opinion.<br>
<br>
6.  Coslin, not to harp, but the voting results of a leader who has absolute control over the voting process should be taken with a grain of salt (see - Slobadan Milosevic)<br>
<br>
Also, if you want to compare body counts - take a trip to Vietnam.  While I'm not detracting from the horrific acts of last year, the people who lived under the flight paths of USAF B-52s would likely hold a similar view.<br>
<br>
First rule of politics... nobody is innocent.<br>
<br>
7.  We are at a point in our polictical and military development where most conflicts will take place in urban, populated areas.  A scenario for which the U.S, military is woefully underprepared.<br>
<br>
I'm sure more will come up.  But I need to get back to work for an hour or so. <p><div align="center">
