<br>
I believe in the constitution to.  It is designed to protect us from ourselves.  In the US we elect our government, and as the saying goes, because of that fact we may not get the government we like, but we do get the government we deserve.  And that's what scares me.<br>
<br>
Our entire foriegn policy agenda right now is being driven by a public appetite for jingoism.  It has carried over into domestic issues like privacy laws and our right to due process.  I am not comfortable with a nation that creates one standard for citizens and another for folks the government labels as &quot;dangerous&quot;.  We had that experience 100 years ago with Native Americans, and the results will be a black mark on our nation's soul forever.<br>
<br>
I agree, attacking North Korea would be incredibly dumb.  But I don't think the fact that North Korea is a militarily &quot;hard&quot; target, while Iraq is a &quot;soft&quot; one, justifies a double standard.  I want a rational, coherent foriegn policy based on the best interests of the United States, not one based on the best interests of a particular economic sector, or one that seeks to divert attention from pressing domestic problems during an election year.<br>
<br>
The American media today is, in general, laughably biased.  They do in fact tell us what we want to hear.  That's why the evening news that showed Palestenians dancing in the street after Sept. 11th never mentioned the billion dollars a year in military aid the US donates to supress them.  <br>
<br>
You won't see any uncomfortable discussions of the &quot;why&quot; behind these conflicts on CBS evening news, and you certainly won't see it on the Fox channel.  To be blunt, Rupert Murdoch's news edeavors are about supporting a particular political viewpoint, not informing people.  You may get a little of it in some print media (the big 4 - Wash. Post, Wall Street Journal, NY Times, and LA Times being the best of the bunch), but still, not a lot.<br>
<br>
Obviously, I have my own politics and opinions.  But I will reiterate, the #1 threat to America today is ourselves, and our own lack of knowledge and understanding about what is going on around us.  It doesn't matter what your politics are.  Don't take things at face value.  Ask obnoxious questions.  Don't simply assume that since politician X is from the party you support, he can do no wrong.  Read a newspaper every day.  <br>
<br>
A poster above cited their support of the 2nd Ammendment.  If American loses it's freedoms it will not be because the US military stages a coup and we need to use our guns to defend ourselves.  It will be because a blind and apathetic public signed those freedoms away, because they just didn't care or know enough to say no. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ucoslinroguebarbarian.showPublicProfile?language=EN>CoslinRogueBarbarian</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 184<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(10/18/02 2:41:48 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1582.topic&index=37>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_question_mark.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Confessions of a Curmudgeon</span><hr size=1> Eh. sorry. That wasn't the proper place to test that. Pardon Me.<br>
